      <p><em>In Part 1 of the series, I introduced the concept of First-World Privilege Paralysis (FWPP) — a term I coined that describes the phenomenon where the Western world, overwhelmed by guilt over its privilege, fear of repeating historical mistakes, and shame at such admissions, became paralysed in the face of global crises. I commented on how this paralysis often manifests in internal debates that reflect our narrow view of privilege that often ignores the broader, graver injustices that persist globally. However, I discussed that I believe by reframing our privilege as a responsibility and directing our attention outward, we can purge our guilt, quell our fear, shed our shame and overcome this paralysis by addressing some of the most pressing human rights challenges of our time. In Parts 2 and 3, I shift the attention from defining the concept, to outlining the costs. I explore this by highlighting some of the harrowing realities of gender-based tyranny across the globe.</em></p>

